Kane-Greenberg collection of cigar label proofs PR 242
8.48 Linear feet (19 Boxes)
1890-1930
Access to Collection
Open to qualified researchers by appointment only. Materials are stored offsite and advance notice is required for use. To schedule an appointment, contact the Print Room Librarian at printroom@nyhistory.org.
Related Materials at The New-York Historical Society
The Kane-Greenberg Collection of Cigar Label Proofs spans the period from ca. 1890 to ca. 1930 and contains progressive chromolithograph proof books for cigar box labels. These proofs were used to check color quality. Brands from most of the major cigar companies of the time period are represented in the collection. The collection provides a wealth of material for studying the various American advertising themes and iconographic motifs used in the promotion and marketing of a single product. The books are arranged by the letter and number codes printed on them by Consolidated.

This collection should be cited as: Kane-Greenberg Collection of Cigar Label Proofs, PR 242, Department of Prints, Photographs, and Architectural Collections, The New-York Historical Society.

Provenance
Gift of Raymond Kane, Stanley Greenberg, Neil Greenberg, and Morris Greenberg, 1983.
Arrangement Note
Proof books are filed alphabetically by letter, then by number. Books with no letter markings are filed after those with letters. Some proof books are filed in small portfolios, which are housed together, in numerical order. Proof books with no markings are filed at the end of the collection. Cigar brands are noted when apparent.
